leftrear.jpg|centre|120px]]|| [[Type 82 artillery|Type 82]] || 130&nbsp;mm self-propelled multiple rocket launcher ||  {{Flagu|China}} ||6<ref name=pun>https://sites.google.com/site/faminacgm/yuththopkrn-thi-praca-kar-nipa/xawuth-pra-cak/pun</ref>||Its similar to Type75 MRL, type 82 is a 30-tube 130 mm multiple rocket launcher mounted on [[Type 85 AFV|Type 85]] .   \n|- \n| [[File:Multiple Launch Rocket System (MLRS) launcher, 1989.JPEG|centre|120px]]|| [[Weishi Rockets#SR-5|DTI-2]] || 122&nbsp;mm self-propelled multiple rocket launcher ||  {{Flagu|Thailand}}<br>{{Flagu|China}} ||4<ref name=SIPRI/>||The weapon is a derivative of the [[Weishi Rockets#SR-5|SR-5]]\n|- \n! style=\"align: centre; background: lavender;\" colspan=\"7\" | '''[[Howitzers]]'''\n|- \n| [[File:Atmos 2000.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[ATMOS 2000]] || 155&nbsp;mm [[Self-propelled artillery|Self-propelled howitzer]] || {{Flagu|Thailand}}<br/> {{Flagu|Israel}}||24<ref name=SIPRI/>|| The RTA purchased 24 systems, 1 system delivered from Israel. Another is ongoing license-production in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jon Grevatt, Bangkok - IHS Jane's Defence Weekly |url=http://www.janes.com/article/29460/elbit-thai-industry-collaborate-on-atmos-155-mm-sp-howitzer |title=Elbit, Thai industry collaborate on ATMOS 155 mm SP howitzer - IHS Jane's 360 |publisher=Janes.com |date=4 November 2013 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.armyrecognition.com/march_2015_global_defense_security_news_uk/first_elbit_systems_atmos_155mm_self-propelled_gun_arrived_to_thailand.html |title=First Elbit Systems' ATMOS 155mm Self-Propelled Gun Arrived to Thailand |date=30 March 2015}}</ref>\n|- \n| [[File:CAESAR (camion \u00e9quip\u00e9 d'un syst\u00e8me d'artillerie) Strasbourg.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[Camion \u00e9quip\u00e9 d'un syst\u00e8me d'artillerie|CAESAR]] ||  155&nbsp;mm self-propelled howitzer || {{Flagu|France}} ||6<ref name=SIPRI/><ref name=pun></ref>||\n|- \n| [[File:Moroccan M109A5 howitzer, 2012-03.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[M109 howitzer|M109A5]] || 155&nbsp;mm self-propelled howitzer || {{Flagu|US}} ||20<ref name=pun></ref>||\n|- \n| [[File:U.S. Marine Corps Lance Cpl. Christopher Semenske, a field artillery cannoneer with Golf Battery, 2nd Battalion, 11th Marine Regiment, waits for the command to prime an M777 towed 155 mm howitzer during exercise 130504-M-VH365-059.jpg|centre|120px]]|| M425  || 105&nbsp;mm self-propelled howitzer ||  {{Flagu|Thailand}} ||8<ref name=pun></ref>|| Locally built mounted on [[M35 series 2\u00bd-ton 6x6 cargo truck|M35]]\n|- \n| [[File:GHN-45rear.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[GC-45 howitzer|GHN-45]] || 155&nbsp;mm [[howitzer|towed howitzer]] || {{Flagu|Canada}} ||185<ref name=\"armyrecognition.com\"/> <hr>42<ref name=\"armyrecognition.com\"/>||GHN-45 155mm <hr>GHN-45-A1 155mm<ref name=\"GHN-45 155mm\">GHN-45 155mm</ref>\n|- \n| [[File:U.S. Marines in the Persian Gulf War (1991) 001.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[M198 howitzer|M198]] || 155&nbsp;mm towed howitzer  ||  {{Flagu|US}} ||116<ref name=\"armyrecognition.com\"/><ref name=pun></ref>||\n|- \n| [[File:Royal Artillery Firing 105mm Light Guns MOD 45155621.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[L118 Light Gun|L119]] || 105&nbsp;mm towed howitzer  || {{Flagu|Thailand}}<br/>{{Flagu|UK}} ||22<ref name=pun></ref>|| Thai L119 light gun produced under license. \n|- \n| [[File:Royal Thai Army firing LG1 howitzer with extended range ammunition.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[GIAT LG1]] || 105&nbsp;mm towed howitzer  ||  {{Flagu|France}} ||24<ref name=\"armyrecognition.com\"/><ref name=pun></ref>|| Mk l from Singapore Army.\n|-\n| [[File:Spanish-marines-man-105mm-howitzer-19811001.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[OTO Melara Mod 56|M56]] || 105&nbsp;mm towed howitzer  || {{Flagu|Italy}} ||12<ref name=pun></ref>||\n|- \n| [[File:M101-105mm-howitzer-camp-pendleton-20050326.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[M101 howitzer|M101A1 mod]] || 105&nbsp;mm towed howitzer  || {{Flagu|US}} ||285<ref name=\"armyrecognition.com\"/><ref name=pun><