px]] || [[IAI Searcher]] || UAV || {{Flagu|Israel}} || 4 || \n|-\n| [[File:A Raven unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) flies over a Romanian Land Forces base in Buzau, Romania, June 2, 2011, where U.S. Marines and Soldiers assigned to Black Sea Rotational Force 11 are providing Raven UAV 110602-M-GN320-003.jpg|centre|120px]] || [[AeroVironment RQ-11 Raven]]  || UAV || {{Flagu|US}} ||Unknown  || \n|}\n\n==Future equipment==\n\n===Ground forces===\n* '''VT-4 Main Battle Tank''' \u2013 On 13 May 2016 it was reported that the RTA ordered 28 units of VT-4 MBT.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thaiarmedforce.com/taf-military-news/53-rta-news/814-rta-signed-for-vt-4-mbt.html|title=\u0e17\u0e1a.\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e0b\u0e37\u0e49\u0e2d VT-4 \u0e2d\u0e35\u0e01 11 \u0e04\u0e31\u0e19/RTA Buy Another 11 VT-4s (UPDATE II)|first=|last=Administrator|date=|website=thaiarmedforce.com|access-date=2019-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516202146/http://www.thaiarmedforce.com/taf-military-news/53-rta-news/814-rta-signed-for-vt-4-mbt.html|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> The RTA has signed an agreement with China to procure the VT-4 main battle tank (MBT), features an initial 28 units, with deliveries expected to commence before the end of 2016 and conclude within two years. The deal is thought to be valued at about USD150 million. If the first batch of deliveries is successful, sources indicated the RTA would look to procure additional VT-4s as it seeks to meet a long-standing requirement for up to 150 MBTs.<ref name=\"IHS Jane's 360\"/>\n* '''M1126 Infantry Carrier Vehicle''' - In May 2019 [[Royal Thai Army]] ordered 37 refurbished [[M1126 Infantry Carrier Vehicle]]s from U.S. Army and will also receive 23 more M1126 vehicles.<ref>https://theworldnews.net/th-news/army-seals-deal-to-buy-us-armour</ref>\n\n===Indigenous===\n* [[Black Widow Spider armored car|Black Widow Spider]]\n* [[Phantom 380-X armored car|Phantom 380-X]]\n* [[DTI-2]]/[[DTI-2G]]\n* [[UAV RD01]]\n* [[Black Kite UAV]]\n* [[T-eagle Eye III]]\n\n==Historical equipment==\n{|border=\"1\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:80%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n|'''Name'''||'''Country of Origin'''||'''Type'''||'''Service'''||'''Quantity'''||'''Note'''\n|-style=\"background:#cddae7;\"\n|colspan=\"6\"|'''Infantry weapons'''\n|-\n| [[Steyr-Mannlicher M1888]] || {{flagcountry|Austria-Hungary}} || [[Bolt-action]] [[rifle]] || 1890\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Siamese Mauser style rifle|Type 46 Siamese Mauser]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weekendhobby.com/gun/webboard/question.asp?page=7&ID=3810 |title=\u0e04\u0e33\u0e15\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 182  |publisher=Weekendhobby.com |date=30 January 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> || {{flagicon|Thailand|1855}} [[Rattanakosin Kingdom|Siam]] || Bolt-action rifle || 1903\u2013? || ? || Licensed version of [[Swedish Mauser]] and [[Gewehr 98]] produced in Japan for Siam.\n|-\n| [[Siamese Mauser style rifle|Type 47 Siamese Mauser]] || {{flagicon|Thailand|1855}} Siam || Bolt-action carbine || 1905\u2013? || ? || Licensed carbine length version of [[Swedish Mauser]] and [[Gewehr 98]] produced in Japan for Siam.\n|-\n| [[Siamese Mauser style rifle|Type 46/66 Siamese Mauser]] || {{flagicon|Thailand|1855}} Siam || Bolt-action rifle || 1923\u2013? || ? || Licensed version of [[Swedish Mauser]] and [[Gewehr 98]] produced in Japan for Siam, chambered for Type 66 (8x52r) cartridge.\n|-\n| [[Siamese Mauser style rifle|Type 47/66 Siamese Mauser]] || {{flagicon|Thailand|1855}} Siam || Bolt-action carbine || 1923\u2013? || ? || Licensed carbine length version of [[Swedish Mauser]] and [[Gewehr 98]] produced in Japan for Siam, chambered for Type 66 (8x52r) cartridge.\n|-\n| [[Siamese Mauser style rifle|Type 66 Siamese Mauser]] || {{flagicon|Thailand|1855}} Siam || Bolt-action rifle || 1923\u2013? || ? || Export version of Japanese [[Type 38 rifle]], chambered for Type 66 (8x52r) cartridge.\n|-\n| [[Type 38 rifle|Type 38 Arisaka]] || {{flag|Japan}} || Bolt-action rifle || 1934\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Type 99 rifle|Type 99 Arisaka]] || {{flag|Japan}} || Bolt-action rifle || 1940\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Springfield rifle]] || {{Flag|United States}} || Bolt-action rifle || 1923\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Lee\u2013Metford]] Model 1888 || {{Flag|UK}} || Bolt-action rifle || ? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Lee\u2013Enfield]] Mark 3 || {{UK}} || Bolt-action rifle || ? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Nambu pistol]] || {{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}} || Semi-automatic pistol || ?\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Luger P08]] || {{flagcountry|German Empire}} || Semi-automatic pistol || ?\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Rung Paisarn RPS-001]] || {{THA}} || Assault rifle || 1986\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Heckler & Koch G36]] || {{Flag|Germany}} || Assault rifle || ?\u2013? || ? ||\n|- \n| [[SAR 21]] || {{Flag|Singapore}} ||Assault rifle|| ?\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Steyr AUG]] || {{Flag|Austria}} || Assault rifle || ?\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[MP 18]] || {{flag|German Empire}} || Submachine gun || ?\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Thompson submachine gun|M1A1 Thompson]] || {{USA}} || Submachine gun || 1945\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[M1918 Browning Automatic Rifle|M1918 BAR]] || {{USA}} || [[Light machine gun]] || 1945\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Madsen machine gun|Madsen]] || {{DEN}} || [[Light machine gun]] || 1923\u2013? || ? || Locally built and known as the Type 66 Light machine gun.\n|-\n| [[M1917 Browning machine gun|M1917]] || {{USA}} || [[Heavy machine gun]] || 1923\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Type 77 Vicker Armstong]] || {{UK}} || [[Heavy machine gun]] || 1934\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Type 97 automatic cannon|Type 97]] || {{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}} || [[Anti-tank rifle]] || ?\u2013? || ? ||\n|-\n| [[Type 25]] || {{THA}} || [[Shoulder-launched missile weapon|Rocket launcher]] || 1982\u2013? || ? || 73&nbsp;mm anti-tank rocket launcher.\n|-\n| [[M18 recoilless rifle|M18]] || {{USA}} || [[recoilless rifle]] || ?\u2013? || ? || 57&nbsp;mm recoilless rifle.\n|-\n|